AI Security & Authentication Topics – Research Notes
1. Single Sign-On (SSO)
Single Sign-On (SSO) is an authentication system that allows a user to log in once and access multiple applications without logging in again.

Example:
Logging into a Google account allows access to Gmail, YouTube, Google Drive, and other services without separate logins.

Benefits:
• Better user experience
• Saves time
• Centralized authentication
• Reduced password fatigue

How it works:
1. User tries to access an application.
2. Application redirects user to Identity Provider (IdP).
3. User enters credentials.
4. IdP verifies identity.
5. User receives authentication token and accesses multiple services.
2. SAML (Security Assertion Markup Language)
SAML is a protocol used to exchange authentication and authorization information between systems. It is commonly used to implement Single Sign-On in enterprise systems.

Components:
• User
• Identity Provider (IdP)
• Service Provider (SP)

Process:
1. User requests access to application.
2. Application redirects user to IdP.
3. IdP authenticates the user.
4. IdP sends a SAML assertion to the service provider.
5. Access is granted.
3. OpenID Connect (OIDC)
OpenID Connect is an authentication protocol built on top of OAuth 2.0. It allows applications to verify the identity of a user.

Example:
Login with Google or Login with Microsoft.

Process:
1. User clicks login using provider.
2. Application redirects to OpenID provider.
3. Provider authenticates user.
4. Provider sends ID token.
5. User gains access.

OIDC is commonly used in modern web and mobile applications.
4. OAuth 2.0
OAuth 2.0 is an authorization framework that allows applications to access user data without sharing passwords.

Roles:
• Resource Owner (User)
• Client Application
• Authorization Server
• Resource Server

Working:
1. User grants permission to an application.
2. Authorization server generates an access token.
3. Application uses the token to access specific resources.

Benefits:
• Improved security
• No password sharing
• Controlled access to data
5. JWT (JSON Web Token)
JWT is a compact token format used for secure information exchange between systems.

Structure:
Header.Payload.Signature

Header:
Contains token type and algorithm.

Payload:
Contains user information such as user ID, role, or permissions.

Signature:
Ensures the token has not been modified.

JWT is widely used in API authentication and modern web applications.
6. Session vs Token Authentication
Session Authentication:
• Server stores user session information.
• Browser stores a session ID in cookies.
• Server checks session ID for each request.

Token Authentication:
• Server generates a token (usually JWT).
• Client stores the token.
• Token is sent with every request.

Session authentication is common in traditional websites, while token authentication is widely used in APIs and modern applications.
7. CSRF (Cross-Site Request Forgery)
CSRF is a security attack where a malicious website tricks a logged-in user into performing unwanted actions on another site.

Example:
A user logged into a bank website visits a malicious page that secretly sends a transfer request.

Prevention methods:
• CSRF tokens
• SameSite cookies
• Double submit cookies
8. CORS (Cross-Origin Resource Sharing)
CORS is a browser security mechanism that controls how resources from one domain can be requested by another domain.

Example:
A frontend running on localhost:3000 requesting data from api.website.com.

Servers allow access using headers such as:
Access-Control-Allow-Origin

CORS enables secure communication between different web applications.
9. HTTPS and TLS
HTTPS is the secure version of HTTP used for communication between a browser and a server.

TLS (Transport Layer Security) encrypts the communication to ensure:
• Confidentiality
• Data integrity
• Authentication

Websites using HTTPS display a lock icon in the browser.
10. TCP Handshake vs TLS Handshake
TCP Handshake:
Used to establish a network connection.

Three steps:
1. SYN
2. SYN-ACK
3. ACK

TLS Handshake:
Used to establish secure encrypted communication.

Steps include:
• Client Hello
• Server Hello
• Certificate verification
• Key exchange
• Secure communication begins
11. Redis and its Use Cases
Redis is an in-memory database used for high-speed data storage and retrieval.

Features:
• Extremely fast
• Key-value storage
• Supports multiple data structures

Common use cases:
• Caching frequently accessed data
• Session storage
• Real-time analytics
• Gaming leaderboards
• Message queues

Redis improves performance by reducing the load on traditional databases.